The best way that I found so far is ignoring base class properties via the `@JsonIgnoreProperties` annotation. 

I annotated my base exception class(`ApplicationException`) with `@JsonIgnoreProperties` and give all base class properties.

such that;
```
@JsonIgnoreProperties({ &quot;stackTrace&quot;, &quot;cause&quot;,&quot;suppressed&quot;, &quot;localizedMessage&quot;})
public class ApplicationException extends RuntimeException{
```

I am still open to other solutions.

Just create a bean you expect in response:
```
public class ErrorResponse {
    private final ApplicationException delegate;

    public ErrorResponse(ApplicationException delegate) {
        this.delegate = delegate;
    }

    public int    getResultCode()     { delegate.getResultCode(); }
    public String getMessage()        { ... }
    public String getHttpStatusCode() { ... }
    public String thrownAt()          { ... }
}
```

And then return it:
```
return new ResponseEntity&lt;&gt;(
    new ErrorResponse(applicationException),
    HttpStatus.valueOf(applicationException.getHttpStatusCode())
);
```

This way your response would NOT be affected by later code or JDK changes.

